frq_section.prompt:
A school maintains a seating arrangement for a classroom as a 2D grid of student names. The class is represented by the SeatingArrangement class shown below.

public class SeatingArrangement {
    /** A 2D array of student names; unused seats hold the empty string "" (never null). */
    private String[][] seats;

    /** Constructs a SeatingArrangement with the given list of names placed into a grid
     *  with the given number of rows and columns. See part (a). */
    public SeatingArrangement(String[] names, int rows, int cols) { /* implementation in part (a) */ }

    /** Returns the name (or "") seated at row r, column c. */
    public String getSeat(int r, int c) { return seats[r][c]; }
}

Write the constructor SeatingArrangement(String[] names, int rows, int cols). The constructor must:
  - Create the seats field as a new 2D String array with the given number of rows and columns. You may assume rows * cols >= names.length and that rows and cols are both positive.
  - Fill the grid in row-major order (left to right within a row, top row first) with the names from the names array, in the order they appear in names.
  - Initialize any unused cells (cells not filled by a name) to the empty string "" — NOT null.

frq_section.reference_solution:
public class SeatingArrangement {
    private String[][] seats;

    public SeatingArrangement(String[] names, int rows, int cols) {
        seats = new String[rows][cols];
        int idx = 0;
        for (int r = 0; r < rows; r++) {
            for (int c = 0; c < cols; c++) {
                if (idx < names.length) {
                    seats[r][c] = names[idx];
                    idx++;
                } else {
                    seats[r][c] = "";
                }
            }
        }
    }

    public String getSeat(int r, int c) {
        return seats[r][c];
    }
}

